    {
      "type": "grammar",
      "title": "Formal vs. Informal Address",
      "explanation": "Serbian distinguishes between formal and informal ways of addressing people, much like French 'tu' and 'vous'. Use 'ti' (ти) when speaking to friends, family, children, or peers your age. Use 'Vi' (Ви) — always capitalized in writing — when speaking to strangers, elders, authority figures, or in professional settings. Verb endings change accordingly: 'Kako si?' (informal) becomes 'Kako ste?' (formal). Similarly, 'Izvini' (informal sorry) becomes 'Izvinite' (formal sorry). When in doubt, start with the formal form — Serbians will often tell you 'Možemo na ti' (We can use informal), inviting you to switch.",
      "examples": [
        {
          "english": "How are you? (informal)",
          "serbian_cyrillic": "Како си?",
          "serbian_latin": "Kako si?"
        },
        {
          "english": "How are you? (formal)",
          "serbian_cyrillic": "Како сте?",
          "serbian_latin": "Kako ste?"
        },
        {
          "english": "Excuse me (informal)",
          "serbian_cyrillic": "Извини",
          "serbian_latin": "Izvini"
        },
        {
          "english": "Excuse me (formal)",
          "serbian_cyrillic": "Извините",
          "serbian_latin": "Izvinite"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "cultural_note",
      "title": "Serbian Greeting Customs: Three Kisses",
      "content": "When Serbians greet close friends and family, they typically exchange three kisses on alternating cheeks (right-left-right). This tradition is rooted in Orthodox Christian culture, where the number three holds symbolic significance related to the Holy Trinity. A handshake is the norm for more formal or first-time introductions. Men often shake hands firmly while maintaining eye contact. Among close male friends, a handshake combined with a pat on the back or even a hug is common. Note that Serbians may stand closer during conversation than you might be used to — this is a sign of warmth, not intrusion. When entering someone's home, it is customary to remove your shoes, and the host will almost always offer you something to drink."
    }
